<TITLE> Kaptai hydro plant risks closure </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Al Amin Dewan Chittagong, Apr 13 (bdnews24.com)  The Kaptai Hydropower Station, Bangladesh's lone hydropower plant, will have to shut down in 20 days for shortage of water. The station's managing engineer Ferdous Ali said on Tuesday that the power plant needed 68 MSL (mean sea level) of water in the Kaptai Lake to keep running. "The water decreased to 77.65 MSL today. Generation at the plant will shut in 20 days if there is no rain." He told bdnews24.com that water level in the lake was falling everyday. "On Tuesday water level fell by 0.32 feet. It will be down by 0.4 feet on Wednesday and another 0.6 feet on Thursday." Currently three units, with a combined generation capacity of 130MW, of the five-unit plant are running, generating 100MW everyday. The other two are shut for repairing. Chief engineer at the station told bdnews24.com that generation will be falling with the decrease of water level. The total installed capacity of the station is 230MW. bdne
